<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Dunno how many of you know about our <A HREF="http://www.crgaming.com" TARGET=_blank>www.crgaming.com</A>  site, but it has a lot of interesting articles like this one:<BR> <A HREF="http://www.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=15" TARGET=_blank>www.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=15</A> <P>The summary of this article?  The online gaming industry's potential is enormous.  More enormous than just eq2 and Star Wars can handle.<P>Diversity is important.  One medium cannot rule the day.  Can you imagine movie theatres only showing action flicks?  It's just unfathomable.  There are too many people that just don't like the same things.<P>Of course you might think that most of the mmorpgs we discuss are within the same genre so action flicks might not be a good example.<P>Well even within the action genre there are differences.  Personally I'm a jackie chan fan.  He does his own stunts.  They don't have to cut out of his action scenes every 2 seconds to make them work and can do close ups because it's actually him.  The greater degree of realism impresses and appeals to me.  However, some people like the fake utter BS that is in movies like mission impossible, or any of jet li's stuff.  Now while this does not appeal to me, these movies are still successful and thus should not be discontinued based on my personal preferences.<P>What you are saying is the exact opposite though.  To you Jackie Chan is good enough.  There is no room for jet li, for Tom Cruise, for anyone else; because the best is already out there.  You refuse to acknowledge that what is best for you, is not best for everyone.  <P>Everquest is not best for everyone.  It certainly isn't what I want.  I'm glad you've found your jackie chan.  Go with it.  However other people are going to want something else, enough so that there will be success for more people.<P>As I said before Sony agrees with this.  Otherwise they wouldn't be pumping out two competing products.  They are comitting two full teams of similar size to both of these projects.  If they didn't expect similar success from both of them they would focus more on one than the other.  That doesn't appear to be the case.<P>Other companies have proven this as well.  Did Mythic take much of a bite out of EQ?  Really doesn't seem like it did to me.  Yet they are boasting 200k+ subscribers themselves and seem to be doing really well.<BR>Where did these people come from?<P>Anarchy Online is floating.  They should have been dead months ago according to everyone's guess.  Yet somehow they managed to hire a consulting group to pull them out of turbulent waters.  Somehow they've managed to get an expansion together.  If AO can float, surely SB can swim.<P>There are a lot of people looking forward to future games that have played Everquest.  Most of them I know don't play the game anymore and won't ever again.  Yet Everquest doesn't seem to be going down in subscription rates because of them, in fact they seem to be going up.  What does this show us?  The industry is growing even as we speak.  The above report is on to something.<P>As the industry continues to grow diversity will play a greater role.  For now the diversity and growth is sufficient that Shadowbane and probably most the others will do just fine.<P>--------------------<P>The barbarians are at the gate, my friends, and they are us. -<A HREF="http://www.terrygoodkind.com/terryinfo/interview/interview2.html" TARGET=_blank>Terry Goodkind</A>
